## Finding: Incident Response Is Absent from Maintenance Phase

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: Phase 7 has 6 skills: continuous_learning, dependency_management, documentation_standards, sop_standards, ssot_update, wi_standards. There is NO skill for incident response or on-call management within Phase 7 itself. The disaster_recovery skill lives in Phase 6 (Handoff) — meaning it is framed as a one-time setup artifact, not a living operational practice. Maintenance is where incidents actually occur and recur. A phase governing the ongoing life of software must own the process of detecting, responding to, learning from, and improving around production incidents. Having incident response only in Handoff implies it is "set up once" rather than continuously practiced, which violates first principles of operational excellence.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill — `incident_response_operations` in Phase 7. Trigger: "Run incident response process for [incident]" / "Conduct post-mortem for [event]". Scope: Active incident lifecycle (detect → triage → mitigate → resolve → post-mortem → action-item tracking), not just runbook templates. Includes on-call rotation management, escalation trees, and SLA breach tracking.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 6 disaster_recovery creates static runbooks; Phase 7 must own the dynamic process of executing, learning from, and improving those runbooks continuously. Without this skill, post-mortems and corrective actions have no home.

================================================================

## Finding: No SLA/SLO Monitoring or Error Budget Management

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: Maintenance is where SLAs are lived, not just defined. None of the 6 skills address: defining SLOs (Service Level Objectives), tracking error budgets, monitoring SLA compliance over time, alerting on SLA breach risk, or reporting uptime to stakeholders. The dependency_management skill discusses npm audit cadence; the disaster_recovery skill (Phase 6) mentions SEV levels but does not define how availability targets are established or tracked. Software systems spend the vast majority of their lifecycle in maintenance mode, and SLA adherence is the primary measurable obligation to users and business stakeholders during this phase.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill — `slo_sla_management` in Phase 7. Trigger: "Define SLOs for [service]" / "Review error budget for [service]" / "Generate SLA report". Scope: SLO definition framework (availability, latency, error rate targets), error budget calculation and burn rate alerting, monthly SLA compliance reporting, and escalation triggers when budget is exhausted.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) and Phase 5 (Ship) establish monitoring infrastructure; Phase 7 must consume and act on that monitoring through formalized SLO tracking. Without SLO management in Maintenance, there is no feedback loop from production reality to engineering prioritization.

================================================================

## Finding: No Performance Degradation Detection or Capacity Planning

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: Systems degrade over time — databases fill up, query plans change as data grows, memory pressure increases, background jobs accumulate. None of the 6 Phase 7 skills address: performance trend analysis, capacity planning, proactive scaling decisions, or detection of gradual degradation (as opposed to acute outages). The disaster_recovery skill in Phase 6 has a "Scenario 8: Performance Degradation" runbook, but this is reactive (what to do when it's already slow), not proactive. First principles demand that a maintenance phase own the anticipation of resource exhaustion before it becomes a user-visible problem.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill — `capacity_planning_and_performance` in Phase 7. Trigger: "Analyze capacity trends for [service]" / "Review performance baselines for [project]". Scope: Establishing performance baselines, tracking trend data (query times, memory, disk, API response times), forecasting resource exhaustion, and generating capacity recommendations before limits are hit.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Connects to Phase 5 (Ship) monitoring setup; feeds back into Phase 2 (Design) when architectural changes are required to address capacity limits.

================================================================

## Finding: No Security Patch Management or CVE Response Workflow

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: The dependency_management skill covers npm audit for package vulnerabilities, which is one layer of security maintenance. However, there is no skill covering: OS-level security patches, Docker base image updates, cloud infrastructure patching, CVE triage and risk acceptance workflows, security advisory monitoring (GitHub Security Advisories, NVD feeds), or secret rotation schedules. These are distinct from npm dependencies and represent significant attack surface. Software in maintenance must continuously address the security posture of the entire stack, not just application-layer npm packages.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill — `security_maintenance` in Phase 7. Trigger: "Run security maintenance review" / "Respond to CVE [identifier]" / "Rotate secrets for [project]". Scope: CVE monitoring and triage workflow, OS/Docker/infrastructure patch schedules, secret rotation cadence (quarterly for API keys, annually for certificates), security regression testing after patches, and risk acceptance documentation for unfixable vulnerabilities.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Extends Phase 4 (Secure) posture into the operational lifetime of the system. Without security maintenance, Phase 4 security is a point-in-time snapshot that decays.

================================================================

## Finding: No Technical Debt Management or Planned Paydown Process

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: Technical debt accumulates during Build and Ship phases. Maintenance is where debt must be tracked, prioritized, and systematically retired. None of the 6 skills address: cataloging technical debt, classifying debt by type (intentional shortcuts, architectural mismatches, outdated patterns), prioritizing debt paydown against feature work, or scheduling refactoring sprints. The continuous_learning skill creates instincts and evolves behaviors, but this is individual/AI learning — it does not address the codebase's structural debt or create mechanisms for planning refactoring work. Without this, systems accrue debt silently until it forces emergency architectural rewrites.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill — `technical_debt_management` in Phase 7. Trigger: "Catalog technical debt for [project]" / "Plan tech debt paydown sprint". Scope: Debt identification and classification, debt register maintenance (what it costs to carry, what it would cost to fix), prioritization against business value, and sprint allocation recommendations (e.g., 20% capacity to debt paydown).
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 3 (Build) generates debt; Phase 7 must own its lifecycle. Without formal debt management, Phase 3 velocity permanently degrades the system.

================================================================

## Finding: No Operational Metrics Dashboard or KPI Tracking

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: Maintenance without measurement is blind maintenance. None of the 6 skills address establishing or reviewing operational dashboards: DORA metrics (deployment frequency, lead time, MTTR, change failure rate), business KPIs (DAU/MAU trends, feature adoption, churn signals), or infrastructure cost trends. The continuous_learning skill tracks AI behavioral patterns; it does not track software system health over time. A world-class maintenance phase requires that every sprint review includes operational metrics, not just feature velocity.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill — `operational_metrics_and_dashboards` in Phase 7. Trigger: "Set up operational dashboard for [project]" / "Review operational metrics for [sprint]". Scope: DORA metrics collection and trending, business health KPIs, infrastructure cost monitoring, and automated weekly digest generation for engineering leads.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Connects to Phase 5 (Ship) deployment pipelines for DORA data collection; feeds back into Phase 1 (Brainstorm) by surfacing what features need improvement based on usage data.

