## Finding: Existing Skills Grade — Depth Assessment

### Gap Type: SHALLOW_COVERAGE
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: Grading each skill against first-principles coverage for a maintenance phase:

1. continuous_learning (v2) — SURFACE depth for maintenance. Excellent depth for AI tooling. Irrelevant to system operations.
2. dependency_management — ADEQUATE depth. Covers npm/JS ecosystem well (audit, update cadence, license check, supply chain, Dependabot). Missing: non-npm ecosystems (Python pip, Docker images, Terraform providers, OS packages), multi-repo dependency graphs, SBOM generation for compliance.
3. documentation_standards — THOROUGH depth for document template creation. SURFACE depth for documentation maintenance (no coverage of doc auditing, staleness detection, or mass-update processes when APIs change).
4. sop_standards — SURFACE (subset of documentation_standards, adds nothing new beyond domain codes and a slightly different framing).
5. ssot_update — SURFACE. Covers only the "add new item to master index" action. Does not cover: automated SSoT consistency checking, detecting stale SSoT entries, bulk migration when processes change, or SSoT governance/ownership.
6. wi_standards — SURFACE (subset of documentation_standards, adds nothing new).

Net: 3 of 6 skills provide surface-level coverage. 0 of 6 skills address operational lifecycle concerns (incidents, SLAs, capacity, cost, security patches).
### Proposed Resolution: See Loop 1 findings for proposed new skills. For existing skills: (a) dependency_management needs ecosystem-agnostic expansion; (b) ssot_update needs automated governance tooling; (c) documentation_standards needs a doc audit/staleness workflow.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Surface-level skills mean developers get templates but no operational guidance, which creates a false sense of completeness.

