## Finding: Phase 6 to Phase 7 Handoff Gap — Operational Ownership Not Transferred

### Gap Type: MISSING_HANDOFF
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: Phase 6 (Handoff) creates: api_reference (Swagger docs), community_management, disaster_recovery (runbooks), doc_reorganize, feature_walkthrough, user_documentation. The disaster_recovery skill in Phase 6 establishes runbooks, severity levels, communication templates, and a maintenance schedule. When Phase 7 begins, it is assumed that operational ownership has been accepted — but no Phase 7 skill explicitly validates or formalizes this handoff. Specifically: Who owns the on-call rotation after handoff? Who is responsible for the runbooks in Phase 7? The disaster_recovery skill has an "On-Call Rotation" section, but it is a template in Phase 6. Phase 7 has no skill that activates, verifies, or operationalizes that rotation. The handoff point between "we created the runbooks" (Phase 6) and "we execute the runbooks as a living practice" (Phase 7) has no bridge skill.
### Proposed Resolution: Create a `maintenance_onboarding` or `operational_readiness_gate` skill in Phase 7. Trigger: "Validate operational readiness for [project] entering maintenance". Scope: Checklist-based gate that verifies all Phase 6 handoff artifacts are in place (runbooks exist, on-call defined, monitoring live, SLOs defined, SSoT current), establishes Phase 7 operational ownership, and sets the maintenance cadence calendar.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without this gate, projects enter maintenance without a formal operational owner, on-call schedule, or validated baseline — creating silent operational risk.

