## Finding: Post-Mortem Culture Infrastructure Is Missing

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: Reverse thinking: "If a project completed Phase 7 perfectly, what MUST have happened?" A project with world-class maintenance would have: (1) a blameless post-mortem for every SEV1 and SEV2 incident, completed within 48 hours; (2) action items from post-mortems tracked to closure; (3) post-mortem learnings fed back into runbooks; (4) a post-mortem database that enables trend analysis (are the same failure modes recurring?); (5) a "game day" practice where teams intentionally trigger failures to validate runbooks. Working backward: none of this can exist with the current 6 Phase 7 skills. The disaster_recovery skill (Phase 6) has a post-incident review template, but Phase 7 has no skill that: schedules post-mortems, tracks action items, maintains a post-mortem archive, or synthesizes learnings across multiple incidents. The delta between ideal and actual is zero operational learning infrastructure.
### Proposed Resolution: Confirmed gap from Loop 1 (incident_response_operations). The post-mortem lifecycle specifically needs: action item tracking integration (with whatever task management system is used), a searchable post-mortem archive, and a quarterly "incident trends" review that surfaces systemic patterns.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without post-mortem infrastructure, the same incidents recur — MTTR improves only by chance, not by design.

